projects.announcement:
Welcome to Cloudticity's Delivery team! We are focused on delivering services to customers via managed services and professional services. To deliver managed services in the most highly efficient manner, we have developed a platform called Cloudticity Oxygen. Cloudticity Oxygen provides tools that help with some of our customers biggest challenges.

Important Links:
* [Standard Operating Procedures](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1HiK7iR00uLAVf7dUFCNwMYdVnXmYPmjq0sert8ODr60) - This is an overview of what we do.
* [Cloud Maturity Model](https://teamwork.cloudticity.com/#/notebooks/216682) - This describes how we coordinate customer activities, how they are prioritized, and how to speak to customer delivery.
* [Cloud Value Journey](https://f.hubspotusercontent10.net/hubfs/3407169/NEW%20gated%20assets/cloud-value-model-CVM-v1r1.pdf) 
	* This describes  a series of successive steps, each of which leads to higher levels of cloud maturity. Cloudticity developed the Cloud Value Journey model to show how the business benefits of cloud accrue over time to stakeholders throughout the healthcare organization.

Additional Notes:
* 2 AWS accounts
One for Production-related assets, one for dev/test/uat assets
Us-west (Oregon) will work for the region for all services right now
* 1 VPC per AWS account
Please use AWS or your best practices for subnet ranges for both public and private subnets
We need an application subnet (private and public) and then a private database subnet
You will need to get with John about subnets we can use in AWS if we will have an always active site-to-site vpn tunnel setup between the VPC’s and our network
Site-to-Site VPN tunnel from the VPC to our production network. John can be a resource for any questions you have here
* 2 EC2 instances (Amazon Linux 2) per each environment
All EC2 instances will be: m5a.large, 12gb primary OS disk, additional 40gb mounted disk (gp2) to /data, all encrypted
Naming convention: physician-portal-ui-${env}-01 and physician-portal-api-${env}-01
Where ${env} = dev, test, uat, prod
* 1 PostgreSQL RDS instance
Engine 11.2 RC1, db.m4.large, general purpose SSD 100GB, encrypted, multi-az, 7 day retention
Naming Convention: physician-portal-db-${env}
Where ${env} = dev, test, uat, prod
* I believe that the ui instance should have public access for 80/443, and then both the ui and api instances need to talk to the PostgreSQL database internally. The database does not need external access at all. The ui and api instances will need to talk to each other. Ben might be able to give more insight into this right now if you need it.
